<subsection xml:id="subsec-5-5-2-power-set-counting" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>The Natural Numbers</title>
<p>
    This subsection can be safely skipped, but it is a fun construction using only the empty set to build the natural numbers, also why I insist that <m>0\in\N</m>.
</p>
<p>
    For this construction we begin with the empty set:
    <me>
        |\emptyset|=0
    </me>
    then we consider the set which has a singular element, the empty set,
    <me>
        |\{\emptyset\}|=1
    </me>
    now we consider the set which contains these previous two sets, namely:
    <me>
        |\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\}\}|=2
    </me>
    next lets collect all these sets in a set, that is
    <me>
        |\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\}\}\}|=3
    </me>
    and continue
    <me>
        |\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\}\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\}\}\}\}|=4
    </me>
    and continue
    <me>
        |\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\} ,\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\}\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\}\}\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\}\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\},\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\}\}\}\}\}|=5
    </me>
    and continue... the diligent student will complete this exercise...
</p>
</subsection>